<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-02-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-02-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="589" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d589">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.00/847.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Smith</persName> to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-17">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 17, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The Department’s February 13. Because of doubt as to the effectiveness of
                            the Cape Haitien blockade and the question of whether recognition of the
                            blockade would not be a partial recognition of the Zamor Government and
                            of Theodore as a belligerent, the entire matter is held in abeyance.* *
                            * Foreign representatives continue to act in complete accord with the
                            Legation, awaiting our action as to recognition.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>